    "comment": "Rationale: The inherent lipophilicity of endocannabinoids (eCBs) limits their transport across aqueous compartments, including the cytosol and synaptic cleft. Fatty acid-binding proteins (FABPs) are chaperones that facilitate the intracellular trafficking of eCBs to their respective catabolic enzymes and nuclear receptors (see also PMID:19307565).\n\nFigure 1, 2: pharmacological inhibition of FABP5 abolishes both phasic and tonic endocannabinoid-mediated control of excitatory synaptic transmission in the dorsal raphe nucleus.\n\nFigure 4: genetic deletion of FABP5 also abolishes phasic and tonic Arachidonoylglycerol (2-AG) signaling.. Experimental description: results: \"Phasic 2-AG signaling was assessed by the magnitude of the DSE obtained in the DRn of wild-type and FABP5 KO mice. We found that genetic deletion of FABP5 abolished the DSE (Fig. 4A, n = 8)\"\n\nThe generation of knockout mice is not described.\n\"We also thank Gökhan S. Hotamisligil for providing the FABP5 KO mice.\"",
